{"id": "duc04-testb-15:10#31", "contents": "Shepard's murder has elicited calls for tolerance of homosexuals from unexpected quarters. At the University of Wyoming, football players will wear yellow and green stickers on their helmets in memory of Shepard, signifying tolerance and peace. In Casper, a conservative city of 51,000, located in the heart of Wyoming's oil belt, tolerance has become the watchword. The Casper Star-Tribune, Wyoming's largest newspaper, wrote in its main editorial that prejudice against homosexuals is just as redneck as anti-black bias, and that violence against homosexuals has created a climate of fear in Wyoming and the rest of the nation."}
